
[1]mob

   MOB, n. [from L. mobilis, movable, variable.]

   1. A crowd or promiscuous multitude of people, rude, tumultuous and
   disorderly.

   2. A disorderly assembly.

   Had every Athenian citizen been a Socrates, every Athenian assembly
   would still have been a mob.

   3. A huddled dress.

     MOB, v.t. To attack in a disorderly crowd; to harass tumultuously.

   1. To wrap up in a cowl or vail.
